Use **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It spins up your app in-process with an in-memory test server — no real ports, no real HTTP listener.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

### Example test

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        // Initialize first (MCP requires it)
        await InitializeAsync();

        var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };
        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }

    private async Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        var init = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 0, method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };
        await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", init);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your app in-process; `CreateClient()` returns an `HttpClient` wired to it |
| **Override services** | Use `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in mocks/fakes |
| **Full pipeline** | Middleware, routing, serialization — everything runs as in production |
| **MCP specifics** | Always send `initialize` first; use JSON-RPC 2.0 envelope; adjust the endpoint path (`/mcp`, `/sse`, etc.) to match your server's route |

For **SSE-based** MCP transports, read the response stream incrementally instead of `ReadFromJsonAsync`:

```csharp
var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);
while (await reader.ReadLineAsync() is { } line)
{
    // parse "data: {...}" SSE frames
}
```

This gives you real protocol-level coverage with the speed of an in-process test.
